<subSubSection box="[151,1436,618,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,618,1905]" box="[151,1436,618,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,1436,618,645]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,1436,618,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[151,309,618,645]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,309,618,645]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Lysmata rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to the Indo-Pacific and introduced in its 
<materialsCitation box="[882,1436,618,645]" country="Brazil" location="Atlantic" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus box="[882,933,619,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<collectingCountry box="[1039,1114,618,644]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
) and the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03DF38488D29FFE7B5EAFD82FC4BF8CD:8EA9DF858D29FFE7B1BCFD83FAC3FD38" box="[1217,1313,618,644]" country="Brazil" name="Atlantic" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Atlantic</location>
as a whole
</materialsCitation>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="206" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,618,1905]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
At present, determining the natural distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[732,817,655,681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[732,817,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is confounded by the discovery of a phylogenetically close and currently undescribed species (
<emphasis box="[623,646,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. AUS2) collected from north 
<collectingCountry box="[1026,1132,691,717]" name="Australia" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Australia</collectingCountry>
, which is morphologically similar (albeit with some differences in the number of carpal and meral second pereopod segments) and likely possesses a similar coloration pattern (thin red stripes with dark transverse bands on the pleon). Although we do not know the coloration pattern of the Australian individuals included in the present study, photographs of Australian “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[164,265,835,860]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[164,265,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (
<bibRefCitation author="Vaughan, D. B. &amp; Grutter, A. S. &amp; Hutson, K. S." box="[292,534,835,861]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="429 - 436" refId="ref24336" refString="Vaughan, D. B., Grutter, A. S. &amp; Hutson, K. S. (2018 a) Cleaner shrimp remove parasite eggs on fish cages. Aquaculture Environment Interactions, 10, 429 - 436. https: // doi. org / 10.3354 / AEI 00280" type="journal article" year="2018">
Vaughan 
<emphasis box="[399,455,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Barton, J. A. &amp; Humphrey, C. &amp; Bourne, D. G. &amp; Hutson, K. S." box="[545,749,835,861]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="61 - 66" refId="ref17900" refString="Barton, J. A., Humphrey, C., Bourne, D. G. &amp; Hutson, K. S. (2020) Biological controls to manage Acropora - eating flatworms in coral aquaculture. Aquaculture Environment Interactions, 12, 61 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.3354 / aei 00347" type="journal article" year="2020">
Barton 
<emphasis box="[628,684,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
) are similar to photographs/illustrations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1234,1318,835,861]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[1234,1318,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenheimer, H. &amp; Rhyne, A. L." box="[195,537,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="298 - 304" refId="ref21261" refString="Laubenheimer, H. &amp; Rhyne, A. L. (2010) Lysmata rauli, a new species of peppermint shrimp, (Decapoda: Hippolytidae) from the southwestern Atlantic. Zootaxa, 2372 (1), 298 - 304. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2372.1.23" type="journal article" year="2010">Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[549,784,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
<emphasis box="[660,717,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Almeida, A. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. de &amp; Hirose, G. L. &amp; Alves, D. F. R." box="[795,1024,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="257 - 267" refId="ref16517" refString="Almeida, A. S., Barros-Alves, S. de P., Hirose, G. L. &amp; Alves, D. F. R. (2018) Reproductive output of the ornamental shrimp Lysmata vittata (Stimpson, 1860) (decapoda: Caridea) in wild populations and under different maturation diets. Invertebrate Reproduction and Development, 62 (4), 257 - 267. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 07924259.2018.1509903" type="journal article" year="2018">
Almeida 
<emphasis box="[900,957,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alves, D. F. R. &amp; Lima, D. J. M. &amp; Hirose, G. L. &amp; Martinez, P. A. &amp; Dolabella, S. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P." box="[1035,1233,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="41 - 55" refId="ref16601" refString="Alves, D. F. R., Lima, D. J. M., Hirose, G. L., Martinez, P. A., Dolabella, S. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P. (2018) Morphological and molecular analyses confirm the occurrence of two sympatric Lysmata shrimp (Crustacea, Decapoda) in the southwestern Atlantic. Zootaxa, 4526 (1), 41 - 55. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4526.1.3" type="journal article" year="2018">
Alves 
<emphasis box="[1109,1166,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Alves, D. F. R. &amp; Lopez Greco, L. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P. &amp; Hirose, G. L." box="[1245,1305,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref16694" refString="Alves, D. F. R., Lopez Greco, L. S., Barros-Alves, S. P. &amp; Hirose, G. L. (2019) Sexual system, reproductive cycle and embryonic development of the red-striped shrimp Lysmata vittata, an invader in the western Atlantic Ocean. PLoS ONE, 14, 1 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0210723" type="journal article" year="2019">2019</bibRefCitation>
), as well as individuals cited as “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[388,490,907,932]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[388,490,907,932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” from 
<collectingCountry box="[571,660,907,933]" name="Panama" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Panama</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pachelle, P. P. G. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; Anker, A. &amp; Lasley, R." box="[674,902,907,933]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="128 - 136" refId="ref22223" refString="Pachelle, P. P. G., Leray, M., Anker, A. &amp; Lasley, R. (2018) Five new records of marine shrimps (Decapoda: Caridea, Stenopodidea) from the Caribbean coast of Panama. Zootaxa, 4438 (1), 128 - 136. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4438.1.5" type="journal article" year="2018">
Pachelle 
<emphasis box="[779,835,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[922,1036,907,933]" name="Singapore" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Singapore</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Anker, A. &amp; De Grave, S." box="[1050,1334,907,934]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="343 - 454" refId="ref16773" refString="Anker, A. &amp; De Grave, S. (2016) An updated and annotated checklist of marine and brackish caridean shrimps of Singapore (Crustacea, Decapoda). Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 34, 343 - 454." type="journal article" year="2016">Anker &amp; De Grave 2016</bibRefCitation>
), and the Mediterranean (
<bibRefCitation author="Abdelsalam, K. M." box="[331,537,943,969]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="124 - 131" refId="ref16184" refString="Abdelsalam, K. M. (2018) First record of exotic Lysmatid shrimp Lysmata vittata (Stimpson, 1860) (Decapoda: Caridea: Lysmatidae) from the Egyptian Mediterranean coast. Mediterranean Marine Science, 19 (1), 124 - 131. https: // doi. org / 10.12681 / mms. 15591" type="journal article" year="2018">Abdelsalam 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, both species are likely to tolerate tropical conditions and could overlap in large portions of the Indo-Pacific. Thus, given that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[836,937,979,1004]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[836,937,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is likely restricted to the temperate/subtropical waters of the northern Indo-Pacific and 
<collectingCountry box="[643,797,1015,1041]" name="New Zealand" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, it is difficult to reclassify historic reports of “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1322,1424,1015,1040]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1322,1424,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” from the tropical Indo-Pacific as either 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[610,696,1051,1077]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[610,696,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<emphasis box="[740,763,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. AUS2. However, natural biogeographic barriers in the region, such as the Sunda Shelf can affect gene flow and aid speciation events (
<bibRefCitation author="Briggs, J. C. &amp; Bowen, B. W." box="[1055,1316,1087,1113]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="1023 - 1035" refId="ref18494" refString="Briggs, J. C. &amp; Bowen, B. W. (2013) Marine shelf habitat: Biogeography and evolution. Journal of Biogeography, 40 (6), 1023 - 1035. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jbi. 12082" type="journal article" year="2013">Briggs &amp; Bowen 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bowen, B. W. &amp; Gaither, M. R. &amp; DiBattista, J. D. &amp; Iacchei, M. &amp; Andrews, K. R. &amp; Grant, W. S. &amp; Toonen, R. J. &amp; Briggs, J. C." pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="7962 - 7969" refId="ref18338" refString="Bowen, B. W., Gaither, M. R., DiBattista, J. D., Iacchei, M., Andrews, K. R., Grant, W. S., Toonen, R. J. &amp; Briggs, J. C. (2016) Comparative phylogeography of the ocean planet. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 113 (29), 7962 - 7969. https: // doi. org / 10.1073 / pnas. 1602404113" type="journal article" year="2016">
Bowen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
) and may provide insight into the biogeography of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[838,924,1123,1149]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[838,924,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[982,1005,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. AUS2. A directed sampling effort throughout the wider Indo-Pacific is required to determine the distribution of both species and others once confused with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[208,310,1195,1220]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[208,310,1195,1220]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="206" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,618,1905]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
Our analyses confirm the occurrence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[649,732,1231,1257]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[649,732,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Panama, Brazil, Thailand, and Hong Kong. We posit that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to the subtropical and tropical Indo-Pacific and introduced in the western Atlantic, including the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1267,1293]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">type</typeStatus>
locality, Salvador, northeastern Brazil. The phylogenetic and geographic affinity between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1154,1237,1303,1329]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[1154,1237,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other species that naturally occur in the Indo-Pacific suggests 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[692,776,1339,1365]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[692,776,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to this region. We observed in our phylogeny that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[151,235,1375,1401]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[151,235,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprised a monophyletic lineage with 
<emphasis box="[693,716,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. AUS2 and 
<emphasis box="[885,908,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. 
<collectingCountry box="[954,1046,1375,1401]" name="China" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">CHINA</collectingCountry>
, two species from the Indo-Pacific (fig. 4). This clade was sister to a clade that included four other species from the Indo-Pacific (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1252,1356,1411,1436]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1252,1356,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[1372,1395,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. AUS1, 
<taxonomicName box="[235,337,1447,1473]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dispar">
<emphasis box="[235,337,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. dispar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okuno &amp; Fiedler" authorityYear="2010" box="[398,489,1447,1473]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lipkei">
<emphasis box="[398,489,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. lipkei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,618,1905]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[317,419,1483,1508]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[317,419,1483,1508]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the western Atlantic, we assume ballast water was the introduction vector for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1323,1407,1483,1509]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[1323,1407,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,223,1519,1545]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. To date, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[332,416,1519,1545]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[332,416,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported along a large swath of Brazilian coastline, from Ilha de Anhatomirim in the south to the Vaza-Barris estuary in the north (
<bibRefCitation author="Alves, D. F. R. &amp; Lima, D. J. M. &amp; Hirose, G. L. &amp; Martinez, P. A. &amp; Dolabella, S. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P." box="[693,886,1555,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="41 - 55" refId="ref16601" refString="Alves, D. F. R., Lima, D. J. M., Hirose, G. L., Martinez, P. A., Dolabella, S. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P. (2018) Morphological and molecular analyses confirm the occurrence of two sympatric Lysmata shrimp (Crustacea, Decapoda) in the southwestern Atlantic. Zootaxa, 4526 (1), 41 - 55. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4526.1.3" type="journal article" year="2018">
Alves 
<emphasis box="[766,821,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pachelle, P. P. G. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; Anker, A. &amp; Lasley, R." box="[897,1118,1555,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="128 - 136" refId="ref22223" refString="Pachelle, P. P. G., Leray, M., Anker, A. &amp; Lasley, R. (2018) Five new records of marine shrimps (Decapoda: Caridea, Stenopodidea) from the Caribbean coast of Panama. Zootaxa, 4438 (1), 128 - 136. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4438.1.5" type="journal article" year="2018">
Pachelle 
<emphasis box="[998,1054,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
, 2020; 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos, R. de &amp; Alves, D. F. R. &amp; Carvalho-Batista, A." box="[1199,1401,1555,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="1 - 13" refId="ref23026" refString="Santos, R. de C., Alves, D. F. R. &amp; Carvalho-Batista, A. (2021) Shrimps of genus Lysmata Risso, 1816 (Caridea: Lysmatidae) from Queimada Grande Island region, southeastern Brazil. Nauplius, 29, 1 - 13. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 2358 - 2936 e 2021032" type="journal article" year="2021">
Santos 
<emphasis box="[1279,1335,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
). It is uncertain if the Panamanian populations resulted from separate introduction events or if shrimp moved northward naturally from 
<collectingCountry box="[319,391,1627,1653]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pachelle, P. P. G. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; Anker, A. &amp; Lasley, R." box="[401,639,1627,1653]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="128 - 136" refId="ref22223" refString="Pachelle, P. P. G., Leray, M., Anker, A. &amp; Lasley, R. (2018) Five new records of marine shrimps (Decapoda: Caridea, Stenopodidea) from the Caribbean coast of Panama. Zootaxa, 4438 (1), 128 - 136. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4438.1.5" type="journal article" year="2018">
Pachelle 
<emphasis box="[502,558,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
(2018)
</bibRefCitation>
surmised the introduction of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[968,1052,1627,1653]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[968,1052,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cited as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1159,1261,1627,1652]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1159,1261,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in the Western Atlantic resulted from a recent and very quick invasion. Reinforcing this hypothesis are the introductions of other Asian decapod crustaceans within 
<collectingCountry box="[541,612,1699,1725]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, including another lysmatid shrimp, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okuno &amp; Fiedler" authorityYear="2010" box="[1025,1117,1699,1725]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lipkei">
<emphasis box="[1025,1117,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. lipkei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pachelle, P. P. G. &amp; Anker, A. &amp; Mendes, C. B. &amp; Bezerra, L. E. A." box="[1133,1361,1699,1725]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="1 - 63" refId="ref22143" refString="Pachelle, P. P. G., Anker, A., Mendes, C. B. &amp; Bezerra, L. E. A. (2016) Decapod crustaceans from the state of Ceara, northeastern Brazil: an updated checklist of marine and estuarine species, with 23 new records. Zootaxa, 4131 (1), 1 - 63. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4131.1.1" type="journal article" year="2016">
Pachelle 
<emphasis box="[1237,1294,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alves, D. F. R. &amp; Lima, D. J. M. &amp; Hirose, G. L. &amp; Martinez, P. A. &amp; Dolabella, S. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P." pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="41 - 55" refId="ref16601" refString="Alves, D. F. R., Lima, D. J. M., Hirose, G. L., Martinez, P. A., Dolabella, S. S. &amp; Barros-Alves, S. P. (2018) Morphological and molecular analyses confirm the occurrence of two sympatric Lysmata shrimp (Crustacea, Decapoda) in the southwestern Atlantic. Zootaxa, 4526 (1), 41 - 55. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4526.1.3" type="journal article" year="2018">
Alves 
<emphasis box="[151,209,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
), the alpheid shrimp 
<taxonomicName authority="Ortmann 1894" authorityName="Ortmann" authorityYear="1894" box="[519,915,1735,1761]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Athanas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimorphus">
<emphasis box="[519,739,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Athanas dimorphus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ortmann, A." box="[748,915,1735,1761]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="3 - 80" refId="ref22089" refString="Ortmann, A. (1894) Crustaceen. In: Semon, R. W (Ed.), Zoologische Forschungsreisen in Australien und dem malayischen Archipel. Vol. 08. Denkschriften der Medicinisch-Naturwissenschaftlichen Geselschaft zu Jena. Verlag Von Gustav Fischer, Jena, pp. 3 - 80." type="book chapter" year="1894">Ortmann 1894</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and the swimming crab 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Milne-Edwards 1867" authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1867" class="Malacostraca" family="Portunidae" genus="Charybdis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helleri">
<emphasis box="[1203,1402,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Charybdis helleri</emphasis>
A. 
<bibRefCitation author="Milne-Edwards, A." box="[151,389,1771,1797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="263 - 288" refId="ref21811" refString="Milne-Edwards, A. (1867) Descriptions de quelques especes nouvelles de Crustaces Brachyoures, Tribu des Oxyrhinques. Familie des Maiens. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 4 (7), 263 - 288." type="journal article" year="1867">Milne-Edwards 1867</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pachelle, P. P. G. &amp; Mendes, C. B. &amp; Anker, A." box="[405,633,1771,1797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="87 - 96" refId="ref22292" refString="Pachelle, P. P. G., Mendes, C. B. &amp; Anker, A. (2011) The Indo-West Pacific alpheid shrimp Athanas dimorphus Ortmann, 1894: first record for Brazil and the western Atlantic. Nauplius, 19 (1), 87 - 96." type="journal article" year="2011">
Pachelle 
<emphasis box="[510,567,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Almeida, A. O. &amp; Simoes, S. &amp; Costa, R. C. &amp; Mantelatto, F. L." box="[645,875,1771,1797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="557 - 565" refId="ref16429" refString="Almeida, A. O., Simoes, S. M, Costa, R. C. &amp; Mantelatto, F. L. (2012) Alien shrimps in evidence: new records of the genus Athanas Leach, 1814 on the coast of Sao Paulo, southern Brazil (Caridea: Alpheidae). Helgoland Marine Research, 66 (4), 557 - 565. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10152 - 012 - 0291 - 6" type="journal article" year="2012">
Almeida 
<emphasis box="[749,807,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
). Given the documented occurrence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1321,1406,1771,1797]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[1321,1406,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,282,1807,1833]" name="Hong Kong" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Hong Kong</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[336,438,1807,1833]" name="Thailand" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, indicating a tolerance of tropical and subtropical conditions, we surmise this species has the potential to spread further northward along the South and Central American coast and the Caribbean and possibly Gulf of Mexico, as well as further south as cooling waters allow.
</paragraph>
